training_organizations.name: DC CFSA – Training Services
training_organizations.description: The District of Columbia’s Child and Family Services Agency operates a Training Services division to prepare its social workers and supervisors. CFSA’s training covers DC-specific child welfare laws, investigatory techniques, family engagement practices, and includes a new social worker academy plus ongoing in-service courses.

training_organizations.name: Children’s Law Center (DC)
training_organizations.description: A nonprofit legal services organization in Washington, DC that provides attorneys to represent children in the District’s family court system. Children’s Law Center attorneys often serve as guardians ad litem or special education advocates for youth in foster care, ensuring the child’s interests are represented in court and they receive needed services.

policies.DefAge_Specify: Under age 18 and up to 21 if in the care of the agency
policies.ReportAnonymous: General public (not mandated reporters) can remain anonymous
policies.Def_OtherSpecify: Imminent danger of being abused and whose sibling has been abused
policies.FatalitiesReview: Yes, reviews are required for all or some cases
policies.Def_Subtype_Neglect: Neglect includes abandonment, lack of parental supervision/parental responsibility, educational neglect, physical neglect, positive toxicology at birth, illegal substance use, exposure to drug-related activity, a child whose sibling has been abused and who is in imminent danger of being abused, and failure to thrive
policies.NearFatalitiesReview: Yes, reviews are required for all or some cases
policies.Penalty_OtherSpecify: For any person over age 18, failure to report sexual abuse is subject to a civil fine up to $300; For mandated reporters, failure to report any type of child maltreatment are subject to a criminal fine up to a $1,000, imprisonment for up to 180 days, or both
policies.Reporter_OtherSpecify: Humane officer of any agency enforcing animal cruelty laws; A public housing resident manager
policies.SafeHaven_OtherSpecify: Custodial parent who leaves child must be a DC resident
policies.ReportInfo_OtherSpecify: Any additional information that will assist in investigating the report of child sexual abuse
policies.AntiDiscrim_OtherSpecify: Personal appearance; Family responsibilities; Matriculation; Source of income; Place of residence or business
policies.InvestQual_TrainingSpecify: A minimum of 80 hours of pre-service training and a minimum of 30 hours of annual in-service training; Under the supervision of their training supervisors, Child and Family Service Agency (CFSA) social workers shall also complete all applied professional training (APT) activities, based on the Pre-Service APT Handbook provided by the Child Welfare Training Academy
policies.InvestQual_ExperienceSpecify: At least 1 year of specialized and directly related professional experience such as attending and/or representing the CFSA at administrative reviews, court hearings, and other meetings; coordinating the implementation of court orders; assisting in determining the appropriateness of established goals, services, and/or permanency planning based on the status findings
policies.InvestReq_MHEvalCases_Specify: When child presents current mental health distress (e.g., suicidal, homicidal, psychotic)
policies.CaseManagerQual_ExperienceSpec: At least 1 year of specialized and directly related professional experience such as attending and/or representing the CFSA at administrative reviews, court hearings, and other meetings; coordinating the implementation of court orders; assisting in determining the appropriateness of established goals, services, and/or permanency planning based on the status findings
policies.InvestReq_MedEvalCases_Specify: Substance-exposed infants; Sexual abuse; Serious physical abuse
policies.CaseManagerQual_TrainingSpecify: A minimum of 80 hours of pre-service training and a minimum of 30 hours of annual in-service training; Under the supervision of their training supervisors, Child and Family Service Agency (CFSA) social workers shall also complete all applied professional training (APT) activities, based on the Pre-Service APT Handbook provided by the Child Welfare Training Academy
policies.FalseReportPenalty_OtherSpecify: The Office of the Attorney General, which determines whether any formal prosecution is warranted
